Kennedy Jr., who is running for the Democratic presidential nomination, on Thursday testified that he has “never uttered a phrase that was either racist or anti-Semitic.”   His denial came days after a video surfaced showing him saying that COVID-19 may have been “ethnically targeted,” affecting Jewish and Chinese people less than others.   Mr. Kennedy has a long history of making comments that have been labeled anti-vaccination and anti-Semitic.   After his opening statement, Rep. Debbie Wasserman Schultz (D-FL) raised a point of order to try to remove Mr. Kennedy from the hearing, saying he violated a House rule aimed at preventing defamatory or degrading testimony.   “Mr. Kennedy has repeatedly made despicable anti-Semitic and anti-Asian comments, as recently as last week,” she said.   The motion was tabled, 10–8, by the Republican-led subcommittee that was set up to investigate the “weaponization” of the federal government.
